Report on the results of the parallel audit of the VAT administration of the Czech Republic and Germany
foreword
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, emphasizes that SAIs are empowered to audit all public finances.
The declaration requires that the courts of auditors have the power to audit tax collection as much as possible.
The Organization of European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) regards taxes as a significant component of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VI. EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenue by the SAIs.
One of the most important steps towards optimizing the audit work of an ACA is the development of a specific public revenue audit strategy.
This is especially true of taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high default risk.
As national economies become increasingly interdependent and interdependent, a situation may arise in which SAIs can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the audit offices of other countries.
One example is the audit of internationally organized fraud, which can lead to significant revenue losses in many countries.
Combating such crimes requires cooperation between the authorities.
SAIs auditing in this area must be willing to work closely together.
The idea for an audit of the VAT and the system MIAS is the VI. EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This review was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of Audit.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating audit offices first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
Based on the evaluation of the available information, we selected the audit subjects for the audit planning.
Achieving effective and effective VAT administration is a long-standing problem, and individual countries (in particular EC Member States) are seeking solutions to improve the system, simplify VAT collection and increase transparency in this area.
We believe that the results of our audit not only help to improve the work of financial management, but can also provide the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international information exchange.
Report on the results of the parallel audit of the VAT administration of the Czech Republic and Germany
introduction
Reference: CZ) 06/27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215
Subject matter:
(CZ) VAT administration following the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union
(EN) Review of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004
the Commission's audit objective:
(CZ) The purpose of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the tax administration in the field of value added tax following the integration of the Czech Republic in the common market of the European Community (hereinafter "the EC") with free movement of goods and services and the Use of VIES1, in particular the control of the use of VAT exemption for intra-Community supplies.
(EN) The purpose of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control, with a focus on mutual assistance in the field of VAT, in accordance with the abovementioned Regulations.
As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations for remedying them should be made.
VAT information exchange system The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NKÚ") and the Federal Court of Auditors ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany pursuant to an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.
The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information gained through international administrative assistance between the tax administrations and the comparison of the VAT management systems in the two countries.
A joint final report on the results of the audits was prepared in accordance with European Guideline No 31 on the implementation of INTOSAI auditing standards.
The audited period covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The parallel VAT audit in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two audit offices.
In addition to the focus on 'exchanges of information' under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004, other closely related issues were also examined, such as the registration of taxpayers, tax declarations and summary statements.
In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation of cross-border passenger transport by coach and bus and the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two countries, differences were found in the following areas:
1) Registration for VAT purposes.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic among others the essential criterion for registration is the exceeding of the turnover threshold laid down in the turnover tax law.
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers receive only one single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, for tax purposes, the taxpayer receives a tax number that applies only to domestic sales.
If German taxpayers require intra-Community sales, they must apply for the issuance of a special identi fi cation number, the so-called USt-IdNr.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonized within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by coach and bus.
In the Czech Republic, the international carriage of passengers by coach and bus is free of VAT, but there is a right to deduct input VAT.
In Germany, the transport service, as far as the route passes through Germany, is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to standardize the situation in accordance with Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of turnover tax (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic the taxable sales tax returns have to be submitted only for tax periods of less than one year (month or quarter), taxpayers in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Sales tax pre-registration and after the end of the calendar year to submit a VAT return.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, taxpayers in Germany have to hand in VAT pre-registrations electronically.
The introduction of the obligation to submit electronic VAT returns in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech tax authorities (see 4.3).
4) Summary messages.
While taxpayers in the Czech Republic are required to submit their summary reports to the tax offices (FÄ), German taxpayers are required to hand in summary summaries to the CLO2.
Correspondingly, FÄ data in the Czech Republic are available as soon as they are submitted in the Summary Reports.
German FÄ the information in the summary reports is only available after their processing by the CLO.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community transactions will be needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the period between the date of the transaction and the update of the VIES data.
This would allow a timely assessment of taxation in the Member State of the acquirer (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same deadlines.
5) International exchange of information in the field of VAT.
For detailed requests for information, the Czech CLO monitors compliance with the three-month deadline.
The German CLO does not monitor the processing times.
As a result, the German tax authorities have dealt with a significantly lower percentage of requests for information received within the prescribed deadline.
Because of these problems, the BRH has recommended the German CLO to constantly monitor deadlines (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is developing its own risk management system (RMS) with corresponding strengths and weaknesses.
The NKÚ and the BRH point out that an effective RMS can not be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS need to be shared and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5.).
As part of the cooperation, the two SAIs audited selected cases of intra-Community transactions implemented between Czech and German taxpayers.
Of these, 31 cases were reviewed together using the CLO's legal options, which raised doubts about the correct taxation or suspicion of VAT fraud.
The SAIs stated:
In some cases the FÄU used the information obtained in the international exchange of information and redefined the VAT liability of the taxpayers concerned.
In those cases, taxpayers either unlawfully claimed the VAT exemption or did not declare the purchase of goods in their VAT return.
In some cases, the FACs could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be recovered due to divergent legislation in the two Member States.
In some cases, the tax authorities of another Member State refused the requested information.
A number of cases were identified in which taxpayers indicated inaccurate sales in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in the VIES was correspondingly incorrect, so the clerks (the FÄ) had to identify in these cases (see 6).
