Registration of taxpayers in Germany
According to the provisions of the tax code (§§ 137, 138 AO) every business enterprise must be registered with the municipality and / or the responsible tax office.
This registration must be made no later than one month after commencement of business.
The municipality forwards the application to the tax authorities.
If the responsible tax office determines that a business has been started but has not been registered, it can also ex officio register the taxpayer retrospectively.
Regardless of whether they are domiciled or non-resident, taxable persons in Germany are required to register for VAT purposes if they fulfill the requirements of § 2 of the German Value Added Tax Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the amount of sales generated.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
For foreign-based entrepreneurs special FÄ are responsible.
For example, the FA Chemnitz-Süd is responsible for those entrepreneurs who are based in the Czech Republic.
As of April 30, 2004, a total of 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered at the company; As of March 1, 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there.
According to findings of the BRH, these FÄ with special responsibilities often denied the registration of so-called fictitious self-employed persons residing in the new Mittelbzw. Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since the free movement of workers is still limited after the accession to the EC of these ten states, these self-employed workers tried to circumvent these restrictions by establishing their own business.
These (fake) self-employed persons do not meet the requirements for recognition as entrepreneurs as set out in § 2 of the UStG, as they are usually dependent on a single client, who determines their working hours and the type of work performed.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must complete a questionnaire from the competent FA and provide information on the company and the business activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a binding form for all FÄ in Germany.
It is processed either in special organizational units within the FÄ or in the general tax units.
With the help of this form, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual taxpayer before the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic sales is based on certain requirements:
The following three (or four) digits indicate which department within the FA is responsible. The following five (or four) digits are the identifier for the taxpayer who is the last digit always a check digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he must, in order to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries, pay a VAT number.
This is allocated by the CLO upon application if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for VAT purposes.
The VAT ID. is automatically allocated by the CLO if the taxable person declares intra-Community deliveries in his VAT returns or in his annual VAT return.
The VAT ID. consists of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On application (eg when he ceases to do business), but only after completion of all taxation transactions (assessment of all financial years) or 2. if the tax authority determines that he no longer operates a business.
As a rule, the validity of the VAT number depends. from the validity of the VAT number.
In these cases the FÄ must inform the CLO about the cancellation of the VAT number, so that the validity of the VAT ID number can be changed. can be ended at this time.
According to the Value Added Tax Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic taxpayers do not have to pay value added tax in the following cases: 1. the turnover of the previous calendar year plus the resulting value added tax did not exceed the amount of € 17,500 and 2. becomes the amount of 50,000 € probably do not exceed.
The so-called small business owners are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor to the deduction of input tax.
Although they do not have to pay sales tax, small businesses are required to register with the tax office and submit an annual VAT return.
A small business owner can declare the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the next five years.
He may then invoice the sales tax and deduct the input tax.
Non-resident taxpayers may appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that they only make tax-free sales and waive their input tax deduction.
The fiscal representative fulfills the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so that he does not have to register for VAT purposes.
The invoices must indicate that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first condition for registration (among others) is the exceeding of the threshold amount mentioned in the turnover tax law.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardized, but differences can occur due to different organizational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the taxpayer receives a tax number for any tax at the time of his first registration.
In the case of his registration for VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community sales.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for VAT purposes receives a tax number exclusively for intra-German sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community sales, he must specifically allocate a VAT number. apply.
Both NKÚ and BRH found that the German two-tiered registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which provides a single identification number for both national VAT registration and intra-Community sales, can lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows retroactive (national registration) in cases where the taxpayer does not register his business with the municipality or the competent FA.
This retrospective registration allows a correct assessment of value added tax for previous assessment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the VAT liability.
As the different registration procedures cause problems, the rules should be harmonized throughout the EC.
The German Parliament has recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Tax Office to every natural person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons residing in Germany for life.
If a natural person starts a business, the competent FA applies for a commercial tax identification number, which is the VAT ID number. serves.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a taxpayer and the allocation of the VAT ID. give.
Work on implementing an IT procedure for the management of numbers is ongoing.
Cross-border passenger transport by coach and bus
The legal requirements in the Czech Republic
Pursuant to the provisions of Article 70 of Law No 235/2004, since 1 May 2004, the carriage of passengers between Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and is entitled to deduct input tax.
The exemption from turnover tax applies even if the transport is carried out by persons who are registered as taxable persons in other Member States or are carried out by foreigners who are taxable domestically.
The return journey is considered as a separate transport operation.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out an economic activity other than the international carriage of passengers by coach and bus, they are not required to register as a taxable person in the Czech Republic.
Cross-border passenger transport was exempt from VAT in the Czech Republic under the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b). The cited text states in the wording:
'For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77/388 / EEC, the Czech Republic may, as provided for in point 17 of Annex F to the Directive, maintain the exemption for international passenger transport until the condition laid down in Article 28 ( 4) of the Directive or as long as the same tax exemption is applied by any of the current Member States. "
The legal regulations in Germany
In accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented by § 3b (1) UStG in Germany, a transport service is carried out where the carriage is effected.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and international passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is taxable in Germany.
Nor does German taxation distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident taxpayer travels through Germany, the part of the carriage accruing to Germany shall be considered as taxable carriage.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the competent FA.
It registers it for tax purposes (see 4.1.2) and issues a special certificate for each registered motor coach in the registration of the taxpayer.
The entrepreneur must indicate his taxable transport services in a German VAT return.
As of March 1, 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with FA Chemnitz-Süd.
If the transport service is provided to a resident entrepreneur, the non-resident taxpayer does not have to pay the VAT himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic purchaser of the services must pay the VAT to the tax office and the net amount invoiced to the non-resident taxpayer. This process is referred to as a "transfer of tax liability" and is in line with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006/112 / EC.
In addition to registration by a non-resident taxpayer and his income tax return, the German tax authorities have several means of verifying the correctness of the tax return with regard to taxable passenger transport:
Customs mobile control groups check the certificates of buses and coaches registered abroad that are used for passenger transport through Germany.
After each check, the mobile control groups submit an inspection record to the competent FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group may require the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident taxpayer may deduct the value added tax paid from the tax liability stated in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts about the correctness of a VAT return, it may order an audit to take place in the IA or may use the assistance provided for in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxpayer refuses to pay the legally fixed value added tax, the IA may request mutual assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76/308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these means of administrative assistance in tax matters for the verification of the VAT return or the compliance with the tax obligation by a non-resident bus operator to be too expensive in relation to the small amount of value added tax on personal passenger transport.
In particular, the audit of the books of a non-resident taxpayer causes disproportionate costs for the taxpayer itself and for the tax authorities.
The latter has to check the foreign books, which requires not only the knowledge of the foreign language but also the foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such a test can be expected to cost more time than a resident taxpayer, even though the test is limited to passenger transport in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must not only accept the audit rights of his national treasury, but also those of the other Member States, insofar as he carries out passenger transport there.
In addition, for each Member State in which even a single passenger service is carried out, the taxable person must fulfill all existing tax obligations in the various languages and the forms of the financial administrations of the EC Member States concerned.
Thus, the correct taxation of international passenger transport services leads to a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between EC Member States and between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT on the basis of the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT in accordance with the distance covered by German national territory.
If a non-resident taxpayer furnishes such a transport service for the first time, he must first register this with the competent FA.
It registers the taxpayer, who must declare the taxable part of the transport service in a tax declaration in Germany.
The law enforcement in Germany is very time consuming.
At least three out of four Czech taxpayers registered with FA Chemnitz-Süd have passenger transport as their business purpose.
The tax revenue in question is relatively low in relation to the administrative burden.
The Member States - which charge VAT in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of turnover taxes - have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionate cost of VAT, cross-border passenger transport should be taxable only in one Member State.
This could be the state in which the promotion begins or in which the service provider is established.
Such a type of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006/112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
VAT returns
Submission and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Insofar as the law does not stipulate otherwise, even if no tax debt has been incurred, the entrepreneur is obliged to submit a VAT return on the form prescribed by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the end of the taxation period.
The tax liability arises on expiry of the deadline for the submission of the VAT return. Excluded from this regulation is, according to Act No. 235/2004, the value added tax on the importation of goods. Here the due date of the tax is determined according to the customs regulations.
If, as a consequence of above-average deductible input tax, a claim for reimbursement arises, this amount will be refunded to the taxpayer within 30 days of the determination of this deduction without the need for an application.
The time limit does not apply in cases where the taxman initiates a tax procedure with regard to the tax liability of the taxpayer.
Pursuant to Section 73 (11) of Law No 235/2004, the right to deduct may be claimed at the latest with the regular tax return for the last taxable period of the calendar year in which the right to deduct input tax was incurred.
After the expiry of that period, the deduction of input tax may still be made within three years of the end of the taxable period in which the claim could have been made for the first time.
However, this requires the submission of a supplementary VAT return.
An amendment to Law No 235/2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, permits the submission of a supplementary VAT return only for the period in which the claim for deduction of input tax could have been asserted for the first time.
A taxpayer must submit a supplementary VAT return if: (a) the sum of the adjustments leads to an increase in the tax liability; (b) he makes corrections which do not change the last known tax liability, but only change previous information; § 49 of Law no. 235/2004 makes adjustments to the VAT rate and the tax liability.
A taxpayer may submit a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
The taxpayer must submit the supplementary tax return by the end of the month following the month in which the facts in question were established.
The sales tax declaration can be submitted electronically either via the Internet or by means of data carriers.
The delivery via the Internet can be done with a certi fi ed electronic signature or without it.
If it does not have an electronic signature, it must also be submitted on data carrier.
The VAT return form contains separate lines to indicate the value of intra-Community supplies and acquisitions.
The value of purchased services must be stated in separate lines of the VAT return.
Some headings are used for automated primary controls under the ATIS system.
The value of goods delivered to other EC Member States to persons who are registered as subject to taxation shall be compared with the data provided by the Czech taxpayers in their summary reports.
The value of purchases of goods from other Member States from persons subject to taxation there is compared, by means of the VIES, with the information in the summary statements of taxpayers from other EC Member States.
