Submission and processing of VAT returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly VAT returns and the annual VAT return.
Those taxpayers who are required to submit advance VAT returns must nevertheless submit an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners who are not required to pay VAT must submit an annual VAT return.
The taxpayers are generally obligated to submit an advance sales tax return by the 10th day after expiry of the calendar quarter in which the value added tax arises (§ 18 (2) UStG).
In the previous year, however, if the VAT liability amounted to more than € 6,136 or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is obliged to submit monthly advance VAT returns no later than the 10th day after the end of the respective month.
The taxpayer may also decide to submit monthly advance VAT returns if he has been reimbursed in the previous year for an amount of € 6,136 (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual sales tax does not exceed 512 €, neither VAT returns nor VAT returns are required.
A resulting VAT liability is payable 10 days after the end of the taxable period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the tax authorities.
(Legal) deadlines for the processing of VAT returns and for the refund of VAT overpayments do not exist.
In order to receive a timely refund, a security can be offered for the refund amount.
In principle, VAT returns, including reimbursement cases, must be processed quickly.
The German sales tax law allows for an extension of these (submission or payment) periods (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension must be requested separately.
If it is granted, submission of the advance VAT returns and the corresponding payments may be made one month later. In the case of monthly reports, however, a special advance payment is required.
This payment will be offset against the VAT liability determined for the pre-registration period December.
If an error is discovered, the entrepreneur must submit a corrected VAT advance notice.
There is no "supplementary" VAT return.
Once the VAT return to be submitted by May 31 of the following year has been submitted to the tax office, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect VAT advance notification, but only the incorrect annual VAT return.
Adjustments of this VAT return to the benefit or disadvantage of the taxpayer are possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT return was submitted.
After expiry of this four-year period, a VAT return can usually be corrected only in cases of trivial tax reduction or tax evasion.
Taxpayers must submit the VAT returns by electronic means.
The FÄ may grant exceptions to this rule to avoid undue hardship.
The annual sales tax return can be submitted either in hard copy or via the internet, with or without certi fi cation.
If the submission takes place without certi fi cation, the taxpayer must additionally submit the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
If no VAT returns or declarations are submitted, the tax authorities are entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover generated by the taxpayer6.
In the event of late submission, the taxpayer may be charged a delay surcharge (up to 10% of the tax liability or up to an amount of € 25,000).
In a previous examination, the BRH found that the FÄ often did not charge this delay surcharge.
In cases where the FÄ charged late fees, the amount was set inconsistently and arbitrarily.
Therefore, the delay surcharge fails to reduce the average delay, in particular when submitting the annual VAT return.
The VAT return form contains separate lines for value data on intra-Community supplies or acquisitions.
Also for the purchase of services there are separate lines.
Non-taxable sales are to be indicated in a separate line of the VAT return.
The sales tax returns submitted on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially designated personnel.
The data of electronically submitted tax returns are immediately available to the tax authorities.
