Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers must submit their VAT returns no later than 25 days after the end of the taxable period.
Depending on the turnover of the taxpayer, the taxable period is either the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
In Germany, taxpayers are required to submit their advance notifications no later than 10 days either at the end of the calendar quarter or the calendar month, depending on the amount of their previous year's tax liability.
The annual VAT return must be submitted by 31 May of the following year at the latest.
The obligation to submit an annual VAT return has some advantages and disadvantages:
+ At the end of the calendar year, the taxable person may correct the errors in the monthly advance notifications by submitting a single turnover tax return;
- If the taxable person corrects his information on intra-Community transactions, the adjustment can not be attributed to a specific reporting period of the ZM;
- The Länder do not compare MIAS data on intra-Community acquisitions of German taxpayers until the annual VAT returns have been processed.
According to the registration (see 4.1.3), German entrepreneurs have to submit a VAT return regardless of the amount of their turnover.
This duty of taxation enables the German tax authorities to check compliance with the minimum turnover threshold for small businesses.
In addition, the responsible IA may reconcile the annual VAT return with the corresponding statements for direct tax and with the annual accounts of the company concerned.
In the Czech Republic, the tax authorities can only check the amount of turnover on the basis of the income tax return submitted.
In contrast to the current regulations in the Czech Republic, German taxpayers are obliged to submit their advance VAT return electronically.
The introduction of the obligation to submit electronic tax returns in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax authorities.
