The international exchange of information without prior request is either automatic, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
The tax officials of other Member States are often provided with information without prior request, which is important for determining the value added tax liability.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected at the CLO.
The exchange of information between the individual Member States takes place electronically.
'Automatic exchange' under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 means the systematic transmission of pre-defined information to other Member States at regular, pre-determined intervals without prior request.
'Structured automatic exchange' means the systematic transmission of pre-defined information to another Member State without its prior request, as soon as the information concerned is available.
The Czech Republic shall inform the other Member States in the automatic exchange of information on new vehicle supplies.
This information shall be obtained by the taxman from the declaration form relating to the delivery of a new vehicle in accordance with § 19 of Law No 235/2004 and from the copy of the invoice issued.
When processing this form, the taxman enters the required data in the corresponding template and forwards it directly to the responsible member of the Financial Directorate, where this data is collected and sent to the CLO for further processing. Thereafter, these data shall be transmitted to the other Member States by the deadline given, at the latest, within two months of the end of the quarter in which they were obtained.
The Czech Republic shall also provide the other Member States with information on sales by mail order which are exempt from tax in the country of origin, on intra-Community transactions which are inadmissible and on potential missing traders.
This information will be communicated to the other Member States via a SCAC form in the spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information originates from the local FA.
The FÄ will send the completed form SCAC 2004 by e-mail directly to the German CLO, which forwards the SCAC forms to the foreign CLO.
The FÄ are instructed to write their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the used SCAC form is monolingual.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the BRH were forwarded in order to ensure the acquisition tax in the other Member State or to prove the tax exemption of the intra-Community supply from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German CLO receives a request for information from another Member State, it will check whether the value of the supplies referred to in the request exceeds the minimum threshold of € 15,000.
If there is no adequate justification for the request, the German CLO denies the information regarding a turnover below the minimum amount limit.
In addition, the German CLO provides the translation of the freely formulated texts in the SCAC form [(B1-17) or (E)] if these are neither in German nor in English.
To answer the request for information, the CLO forwards this to the competent FA, referring to the three-month deadline.
At the various levels of the German financial administration, no further deadlines are set.
Although the German CLO has the technical means to monitor compliance with deadlines, it does not have the necessary staffing capacity to remind the FÄs to respond to pending requests for information.
The FÄ receives the required information by letter from the taxpayer or by carrying out an external audit.
The external auditors usually choose between two types of audits: the VAT special audit, which covers all taxable transactions within a period of several months, or the so-called sales tax review, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
With this short and fl exible form of examination, it is not necessary to make an announcement to the taxpayer and it has proved itself in the investigation of a single transaction.
In the case of an automatic exchange of information, Germany shall provide the other Member State with the following information: - via VAT registration numbers assigned to undertakings located in other EC Member States, - on the refund of input tax to traders established in other EC Member States.
