The tax audit and tax investigation methodology carries out, among other things, risk analysis as part of the methodological control of tax audits, sets priorities for the financial directorates' work schedules in selecting the cases to be audited, draws up risk analyzes to combat tax evasion and collects information from the tax audit Financial management and other sources, and make proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax investigation agencies exist at the financial directorates. Its tasks include the search for taxpayers and industries which are risky in terms of tax avoidance (eg internet shops, gold, pharmaceutical industry), the search for unregistered taxpayers (eg in the internet services, employment services, electronic and print media, etc.). ), investigating allegations of chain fraud and informing the local tax authorities.
Special exam units have been set up in 12 selected FÄ.
These have a regional responsibility and carry out tax audits beyond the local area of responsibility of the FÄ.
The need to set up the special audit units resulted from the increase in perceived new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly in relation to chain stores.
These special units examine the needs of the tax investigators or focus on taxpayers with specific activities, multinationals and taxpayers with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing VAT risks have been integrated into the ATIS system: - the task "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk weight of tax returns, - the task "Selection of taxpayers to audit", with the taxpayers to be audited on the basis of certain tax - the "VIES" task, which gives the tax officials access to the data made available by other EC Member States.
The task "VIES" allows, among others, the following: - Verification of the validity of the VAT ID. of taxpayers from other Member States, - confirmation of the value of goods delivered to a Czech taxpayer, as indicated in the CM by all suppliers of the taxpayer concerned from other Member States, - compilation of a list of taxpayers who have not surrendered CM, - formal Checking the information that taxpayers in the Czech Republic have entered in their CM before submitting this information to other Member States; - Drawing up a list of taxpayers whose sales tax returns do not match the data on deliveries of goods to other Member States with the information in the CM - a list of taxpayers whose VAT returns do not agree with the information on the value of the goods purchased from other Member States, as indicated in the CM of all their suppliers from other Member States13.
As part of their duties to combat tax evasion, the tax officials have access to the data in state agencies such as commercial registers, land registry, motor vehicle registries, business registers, etc.
More detailed information can be found in section 4.4.1 Submission and processing of summary reports in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
Because of their federal structure, the Federal Republic of Germany involves both the Federal Finance Authorities (in particular the CLO) and the tax administrations of the 16 Länder in the development and introduction of an RMS.
Although there are joint working groups for development, neither the CLO nor the tax administrations of the federal states have completely unified data.
At the level of the CLO, Unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as "KUSS" - the coordination unit for turnover tax audits and tax investigations) collects audit findings on fraud in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the federal states KUSS established another database called ZAUBER. There, the tax offices can enter the names of discovered missing traders or VAT fraudsters and also query.
The KUSS coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experiences of the KUSS are brought into the development of the RMS by their participation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organizational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
