In addition, the RMS of the CLO relies on the VIES data provided by the other Member States and generates various types of messages to detect suspected missing traders. As a guide, certain features are used, which usually occur in carousels.
The FÄ der Bundesländer are required to process these communications and, in certain cases, must forward the results of their investigations to the CLO.
The BRH audit has confirmed that all available features need to be included to make it sufficiently likely to detect a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing primarily on a company's sales).
Accordingly, the BRH recommended that the BMF work with combinations of different clues when preparing the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other factors, such as the payment behavior of the taxpayer, the economic activity or the ownership structure of the company.
A second level of risk management exists with the tax authorities of the federal states and focuses on the processing of VAT returns and annual statements.
For example, the system draws up a list of those taxpayers who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their advance VAT return or annual declaration.
This list will be sent to the CLO for the purpose of monitoring the complete delivery of the ZM.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the purchases specified by the taxpayer in his annual VAT return are compared with the data in the VIES.
The tax administrations of the federal states avoid a comparison of the quarterly data, as these would lead to too many discrepancies, which are due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; eg:
- Supplier and purchaser assume different times for the execution of intra-Community sales;
- different accounting records and tax declaration of discounts and discounts.
In addition to the comparison of VAT return data with the MIAS data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms based on information in the VAT returns and certain other indications (eg company name, age of the owner / partner, number of employees and form of payment of the taxpayer) ,
Bavaria has implemented a fixed-risk risk management system that allows a team of anti-tax fraud specialists (hereafter "risk managers") to program their own rules to identify alleged tax evaders.
This system is used in the processing of VAT returns by the FÄ.
Thus, the competent FA receives the advice of the RMS before the sales tax is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, the risk managers must adjust the rules according to the feedback from the FÄ.
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of detected cases of evasion.
Based on these data, the RMS is able to learn the features of tax evasion.
The system produces a monthly list of tax cases with evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent FACs decide on the examination of the taxpayers concerned.
After the audit, the tax inspectors have to report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of their proposed examinations.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rule-based fuzzy system.
Based on many data from processed VAT returns and some other clues, this neuro-fuzzy system (also known as the data-mining system) calculates how likely it is that a taxpayer is involved in tax fraud.
After that, it creates a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, FACs select the taxpayers concerned for review and report the results of the audit to the data center concerned.
The introduction of these three RMS is in progress in the federal states.
As each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems appears to be effective.
Whether the actual effects will bring the expected effects remains to be seen.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in this report to address the specific criteria of RMS in Czech and Germany, NKÚ and BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three German states mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
At present, there is an exchange of experience between the tax authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud - in particular carousel fraud - has proved to be no national but European problem.
The persons involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several Member States.
One Member State alone can not develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS need to be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State. If this does not happen, fraudsters choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The loss of VAT caused by VAT fraud throughout Europe does not necessarily affect the Member State where the initiator is established.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud may be affected.
Therefore, there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
