In the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer was expected to deliver goods worth € 89,424 to a German taxpayer.
As the German declared taxpayer did not agree with the VIES data, the German tax office requested the verification of deliveries and their payment as part of the inter-state exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech tax official stated that the sole director of the Czech company was deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was allegedly a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech taxpayer issued a VAT return and a ZM which had been signed in the commercial register by an unauthorized person, namely the shareholder of the company, after the removal of the managing director.
The accountant of the Czech taxpayer informed the taxman that the capital owner had paid the payment received in euros for the invoiced goods to the company's account.
Cash receipts were not issued.
By requesting the Czech local FA, the NKÚ stated that the tax office had recognized the Czech taxpayer's claim to VAT exemption for deliveries of goods to other Member States worth CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005 ,
The BRH found that the German tax official did not correct the VAT return of the German acquirer, since in the meantime a German court had confirmed the bankruptcy of the German taxpayer.
Since the previous external audit did not show any signs of tax fraud, there was no prospect of actually being able to levy a fixed VAT liability.
20. According to the MIAS data, in 2005 a German taxpayer purchased goods from the Czech Republic amounting to € 4,251,196, after having purchased goods worth € 43,274 in the previous year.
The German taxpayer did not declare the intra-Community acquisitions either in its 2004 VAT return or in 2005.
In addition, he did not declare equivalent value-based sales.
Because of these discrepancies, the German FA submitted a request for information concerning the fourth quarter of 2005 and the first quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community deliveries of goods totaling 167,246,083 CZK.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side asked to check whether the delivery reported by the Czech taxpayer had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech tax authorities stated that the German request could not be complied with because the Czech company had no managing director (or other legal representative).
It is apparent from the documents provided to the NKÚ by the competent taxman that a record of the start of the VAT audit for the fourth quarter of 2004 and the period January to December 2005 was drawn up on 30 March 2006 together with the manager of the Czech taxpayer ,
The taxpayer was at the same time requested by the taxman to submit all the accounting and tax records for that period but did not.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the sole managing director expired on May 16, 2005, without the appointment of a new managing director.
The Czech taxpayer has not paid any sales tax declarations since April 2006.
As part of the parallel investigation, the NKÚ, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community deliveries between the Czech Republic and Germany that were not the subject of a prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two courts of auditors exchanged information about the audited cases via the CLOs of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the competent FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to carry out taxable business in Germany.
Based on this information, the company was registered from June 2005, but received no German VAT ID number.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the manufacture of wind turbines and their delivery to Austria in the name, at the risk and for the account of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient own manufacturing capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the order to a German taxpayer (UDE) based in Germany.
The following figure shows the contractual relationships and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines in his name, at his risk and for his own account for assembly in Austria.
Because of the assembly, its delivery takes place in Austria, ie the delivery of wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
- Because the freight forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and had the latter carry out the transport in his own name, at his own risk and for his own account, the place of delivery of the German subcontractor (UDE) is where the transport started, ie in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient was registered as taxable in one EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the supply of the German subcontractor (UDE) as the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is different from the country of residence of the Czech company19.
Accordingly, this supply is duly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed deduction of VAT in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport started.
However, in some of the wind turbines, transport was from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- The delivery of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- The delivery of the remaining wind turbines, which were manufactured in Germany, took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided both intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community supplies from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) has not declared any intra-Community supplies in its German tax returns or in its ZM issued to the German CLO.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community supplies uniformly as intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic.
The NKÚ noted that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community supplies to Denmark.
To ensure taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, cooperation between at least four tax administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be required, although in this case there are no signs of tax fraud or evasion.
In addition, the NKÚ and the BRH examined cases to show the size of the differences between the statements in the VAT returns and the VIES data caused by the different 2004 legislation.
The audited cases also show that it takes some time before taxpayers and FÄs apply the new legislation:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech taxable supply of goods totaling CZK 792,977.452 reported to a German taxpayer.
During the same period, another Czech taxpayer reported intra-Community deliveries to its other counterpart in the Community to another German taxpayer with a total value of CZK 18,157,265.
From the information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ, it emerged that in both cases electricity was supplied.
Both Czech taxpayers included the abovementioned deliveries in their CM in accordance with the Czech Law No 235/2004 in force in 2004.
In a further review of these transactions, a NKÚ audit group noted that in 2004 there were different legal provisions governing the supply or purchase of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany.
Whereas in the Czech Republic, the taxpayers are responsible for the supply of electrical energy in accordance with the provisions of Law no. 235/2004 as intra-Community deliveries of goods, according to the German legal provisions in force in 2004, this was not an intra-Community acquisition of goods but taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in legal regulations were abolished in the Czech Republic by adopting Law No. 635/2004, which with effect from 1 January 2005 changed some tax provisions.
23. When examining intra-Community supplies or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech taxpayer in his CM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 supplied intra-Community supplies to a German taxpayer with a total value of CZK 240,411,163 and another Czech Taxpayer in his ZM declared intra-Community deliveries to another German taxpayer worth CZK 263,470,776 for the same period.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ revealed that both cases involved supplies of electrical energy.
According to the wording of Act No. 235/2004, which applies from 1 January 2005, the place of performance for the supply of electrical energy is the place where the transferee has his legal domicile, place of business or permanent establishment for which the delivery takes place.
Therefore, the Czech taxpayers should not have specified the electricity deliveries in their ZM for 2005.
The fact that both taxpayers treated the supply of electrical energy in their CM as intra-Community supplies resulted in a difference of CZK 503.881.939 in MIAS.
concluding remark
The cooperation achieved the objectives of the BRH and the NKÚ.
Both audit offices gained in-depth knowledge of the systems of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The collaboration revealed differences in the two systems and in the VAT regulations.
During the parallel examinations, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions came to light.
For some of them worth a further observation.
Based on the audit findings, both SAIs prepared recommendations on the management of VAT.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a check should be part of the follow-up.
The new experience and knowledge gained through cooperation between the two courts of auditors form the basis for the successful conduct of future VAT audits.
